Video Game Sales Analysis Project

Project Overview

In this project, you'll analyze video game sales data to identify patterns that determine a game's success. Working as an analyst for the online store Ice, you'll use this information to help plan future advertising campaigns.

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to analyze video game sales data to forecast the features which make up a video game's success. By identifying patterns and trends across different platforms, genres and regions we aim to gather insights to help make future decisions regarding video game releases.

We identified two duplicate entries with the same 'name', 'platform', and 'year_of_release'. The second occurrence of Madden NFL 13 on PS3 appears to be a mistake, as one row contains more complete and inclusive data. Additionally, we found other duplicate rows where the 'name' field is missing, making it impossible to verify the game's identity. To ensure data integrity we will remove the duplicate entries.

  • What's the total number of records in our dataset?
  • What data types are present in each column?
  • Are there any obvious issues with the data?
  • Do we see any immediate patterns or anomalies?

There are 16,715 records found within the original dataframe with object and int64 data types. Obvious issues with the data include incorrect data types such as for 'year_of_release' (object instead of int64 for analysis) and 'user_score' (object instead of float64). We corrected these in order to perform further analysis on the dataset. Another obvious issue we will need to handle is the missing values throughout the dataset. We can see that 'critic_score', 'user_score' and 'rating' have the highest amount of missing values close to almost 50% of all the data. Finally, we need to format the column names.

We type cast 'user_score' to float64 to facilitate numerical operations and comparisons with other quantitative columns. More than likely there are entries of 'tbd' due to games not having been rated yet. By coercing errors in the type casting call we can deal with these 'tbd' values in the future by leaving them as NaNs for now while analyzing regarding user scores. We also converted 'year_of_release' to type int64 in order to perform statistical analysis for this feature.

We can see high correlations between games that have a missing rating, critic or user review. For a majority of games missing one of these values they will also be missing values in the other two variables listed. The most significant correlation we see is that games missing a critic rating are also missing a user review. We do not see high correlations between missing 'year_of_release' games and other variables (besides a very minuscule negative correlation). Otherwise, games with missing data do have a negative impact on ratings and sales, besides in Japan: it seems in Japan there is a slight increase in sales with these missing scores and ratings.

# Why do you think the values are missing? Give possible reasons.
# Explain why you filled in the missing values as you did or why you decided to leave them blank.

The 'year_of_release' column could be missing data due to older games lacking proper documentation or new games yet to release. Most likely, some games have not been rated yet and that is why they are missing values. Whether a game has ratings or not could be due to a game's popularity and success. Once again, we are incapable of identifying the game with the missing name so we will drop this row. About half of all data is missing 'critic_score', 'user_score' and 'rating'. Since this is a high proportion of the data we should not just drop the rows. Instead, we will create new features that describes whether each row has all ratings or the 'year_of_release' so that way we can build new dataframes in order to analyze the data within these columns.

Step 5 : Hypothesis Tests

Average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are the same.

Average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are different.

Set the alpha threshold value yourself.

Explain:

How you formulated the null and alternative hypotheses

What criteria you used to test the hypotheses, and why

Null Hypothesis 1: Average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are the same. Alternative Hypothesis 1: Average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are NOT the same. The Null Hypothesis should always hold the equal statement. We will set alpha value to 0.05 so we can balance avoiding false positives with finding a correlation. This value will allow us to be confident in our findings without being to conservative.

In[]:
# Test the hypotheses
df_platforms = df[df['platform'].isin(['XOne', 'PC'])][['platform', 'user_score']].dropna()
xbox_ratings = df_platforms[df_platforms['platform'] == 'XOne']['user_score']
pc_ratings = df_platforms[df_platforms['platform'] == 'PC']['user_score']
alpha=0.05
results = st.ttest_ind(xbox_ratings, pc_ratings, equal_var=False)

print('p-value:', results.pvalue)
if (results.pvalue < alpha):
    print("We reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value: 0.14759594013430463
We can't reject the null hypothesis

Average user ratings of the Xbox One and PC platforms are NOT the same.

Null Hypothesis 2: Average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are the same. Alternative Hypothesis 2: Average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are different The Null Hypothesis should always hold the equal statement. We will set alpha value to 0.05 so we can balance avoiding false positives with finding a correlation. This value will allow us to be confident in our findings without being to conservative.

In[]:
# Test the hypotheses
df_genres = df[df['genre'].isin(['Action', 'Sports'])][['genre', 'user_score']].dropna()
action = df_genres[df_genres['genre'] == 'Action']['user_score']
sports = df_genres[df_genres['genre'] == 'Sports']['user_score']
alpha=0.05
results = st.ttest_ind(action, sports, equal_var=False)

print('p-value:', results.pvalue)
if (results.pvalue < alpha):
    print("We reject the null hypothesis")
else:
    print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value: 1.4460039700704315e-20
We reject the null hypothesis

Average user ratings for the Action and Sports genres are the same.

Conclusion

WHAT DETERMINES A GAMES SUCCESS

After cleaning the data and performing statistical analysis we are able to draw some conclusions regarding which factors determine a video games success. Early on we discovered that games with missing reviews have a negative outcome on a games success. We have discovered that around 2008 and 2009 there was a peak in video game sales and since that time sales have been decreasing. This highlights the need for discovering trends that make up a games success. At that time, the PS2 exploded in sales and to this day remains the most lucrative platform for video game sales. We can see that which console a game is released on determines it's success due to the fact that older systems no longer have sales while the newest console (PS4) was making the most sales in 2016. We discovered that games which have a higher critic score are more likely to have a higher user score and have a higher correlation with games that are more lucrative.

Since 2013 (the beginning of the time frame that we chose to analyze for this data), we have discovered that the highest performing platform is the PS4 which beats the PS3 (second place) by more than 100 million dollars. For a new game to have a higher likelihood of being successful, it should be released on the PS4. Even when a PS4 game is released on other platforms, the PS4 versions of games earn the most sales. We can see that Action games are the most popular, followed by Shooter games and Sports games. Finally, we also have discovered that games rated 'M' have performed the best amongst the other ratings, holding 45% of the market (followed by ESRB rating 'E' which has a market share of about 25%.
